🧠 GIT COMMAND CHEAT SHEET (For Everyday Use)
🏗️ 1. Setup (do once per computer)
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "your@email.com"


Tells Git who you are — used in all your commits.

📁 2. Start a New Local Project
git init


Turns your folder into a Git-tracked project.

🧩 3. Connect to GitHub
git remote add origin https://github.com/username/repo-name.git


Links your local project to the GitHub repository.

Check it later with:

git remote -v

💾 4. Save Your Work (Locally)

When you change files and want to save progress:

git add .
git commit -m "Describe what you changed"


git add . = include all files for saving

git commit -m "..." = make a snapshot of your work

☁️ 5. Upload to GitHub
git push -u origin main


Sends your commits to GitHub (first time use -u, then later just git push).

🔄 6. Download Updates (from GitHub)

If you or someone else updated the repo online:

git pull


Fetches and merges the newest version from GitHub.

🔍 7. Check Status & History
git status


Shows what’s changed, staged, or committed.

git log


Shows commit history with messages and authors.

🧹 8. Undo or Fix Mistakes (basics)
git restore filename


Undo local file changes before committing.

git reset --soft HEAD~1


Undo your last commit (but keep changes in files).

🧭 9. Branching (optional for now)

Later, when you work on bigger projects:

git branch new-feature
git checkout new-feature


Creates and switches to a new branch.

⚙️ 10. Quick Reference
Action	Command
Initialize repo	git init
Add files	git add .
Commit changes	git commit -m "message"
Connect remote	git remote add origin <url>
Push to GitHub	git push
Pull updates	git pull
Check status	git status
Check history	git log
| Action         | Git (Terminal)           | GitHub Desktop                |
| -------------- | ------------------------ | ----------------------------- |
| Create repo    | `git init`               | Click “Create new repository” |
| Add files      | `git add .`              | Click “Commit to main”        |
| Commit         | `git commit -m "msg"`    | Fill message box + Commit     |
| Push to GitHub | `git push`               | Click “Push origin”           |
| Pull updates   | `git pull`               | Click “Fetch origin”          |
| See changes    | `git status`, `git diff` | See side-by-side view         |
